{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1872"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.35,0.11,0.38,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3525"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department for a 12-hour episode of lower abdominal pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has a CT scan performed which confirmed the clinical diagnosis of mild diverticulitis, but it also showed a homogenous 1.9 cm lesion in the left adrenal gland. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regard to the adrenal lesion, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further follow-up required","Repeat CT in six months","Adrenal biopsy","Endocrine assessment","Adrenalectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis adrenal mass is an incidental finding and such lesions are well recognised, with an incidence increasing to about 7% in patients over the age of 70. Most adrenal incidentalomas (85%) are benign, with the remaining 15% associated with malignancy or hormone hypersecretion (Cushing\u0027s, Conn\u0027s, phaeochromocytoma). Biochemical evaluation and an \u003Cstrong\u003Eendocrine assessment \u003C/strong\u003Ewith a dexamethasone suppression test and 24-hour urinary metanephrines and catecholamines are indicated in any patient with an incidental adrenal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile most adrenal lesions are benign, there is a risk of malignancy or hormone hyper secretion, and thus \u003Cstrong\u003Eno further follow-up \u003C/strong\u003Eis not correct. Patients with an adrenal mass with benign radiological features and initial negative hormonal investigations, are advised to have imaging at 6, 12 and 24 months, as well as hormonal evaluation yearly for 4 years (e.g. dexamethasone suppression test, 24-hour urinary metanephrines and catecholamines, plasma aldosterone and plasma renin activity if hypertensive). \u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat dedicated adrenal imaging in 6-12 months\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. CT) would be a prudent approach. However, endocrine dysfunction must be ruled out before repeat imaging is suggested.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not recommended unless there is a suspicion of metastatic disease (e.g. history of extra-adrenal malignancy) or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, if the adrenal mass is \u0026gt;4cm, \u0026lt;4cm with suspicious radiological findings, autonomous hormonal secretion or growth of \u0026gt;1cm on repeat imaging, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenalectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended. Given that the mass is 1.9cm and hormonal testing has not yet been performed, this is not the next most appropriate plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small adrenal mass lesions are common incidental findings and most do not need any intervention apart from biochemical and endocrine evaluation"],"references":["Young WF. The Incidentally Discovered Adrenal Mass. N Engl J Med. 2007;356:601-10. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmcp065470","Hanna FWF, Issa BG, Sim J, Keevil B, Fryer AA. Management of incidental adrenal tumours. BMJ. 2018;360:j5674. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/360/bmj.j5674","Mayo-Smith WW, Song JH, Boland GL, Francis IR, Israel GM, Mazzaglia PJ, et al. Management of Incidental Adrenal Masses: A White Paper of the ACR Incidental Findings Committee. J Am Coll Radiol. 2017;14(8):1038-1044. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28651988/","Kebebew E. Adrenal Incidentaloma. N Engl J Med 2021; 384:1542-51."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-30T04:12:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-30T04:13:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","n